<p><ent>Met-</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Meta-</ent>⟦br⟧
<mhw>{

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Met-
<hw>Met-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> }</mhw>.
<ety>[Gr. <grk>meta`</grk> between, with, after; akin to AS.
<ets>mid</ets> with, G. <ets>mit</ets>, Goth. <ets>mi⟦thorn⟧</ets>, E.
<ets>mid</ets>, in <ets>midwife</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A prefix
meaning <sig>between</sig>, <sig>with</sig>, <sig>after</sig>,
<sig>behind</sig>, <sig>over</sig>, <sig>about</sig>,
<sig>reversely</sig>; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>chronism, the error of
placing after the correct time; <ex>meta</ex>phor, lit., a carrying
over; <ex>meta</ex>thesis, a placing reversely.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> A prefix denoting: <sd>(a)</sd>
<def><sig>Other</sig>; <sig>duplicate</sig>, <sig>corresponding
to</sig>; <sig>resembling</sig>; hence, <sig>metameric</sig>; <as>as,
<ex>meta</ex>-arabinic, <ex>met</ex>aldehyde</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Organic Chem.)</fld> <def>That two replacing radicals, in the
benzene nucleus, occupy the <xex>relative positions</xex> of 1 and 3, 2
and 4, 3 and 5, 4 and 6, 5 and 1, or 6 and 2; <as>as,
<ex>meta</ex>cresol, etc.</as> See <er>Ortho-</er>, and
<er>Para-</er>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Inorganic Chem.)</fld>
<def>Having <sig>less than the highest number</sig> of hydroxyl groups;
-- said of acids; <as>as, <ex>meta</ex>phosphoric acid</as>. Also used
adjectively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A prefix meaning <sig>at a level above</sig>, as in
<ex>meta</ex>physics, <ex>meta</ex>language.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metabasis</ent>⟦br⟧
